The hands of evil that are
targeting the energy born

00:02:24.084 --> 00:02:25.919
from mass internet disruption

00:02:26.987 --> 00:02:29.056
caused the International
Space Station

00:02:29.089 --> 00:02:31.825
to begin hurdling through
space towards Earth.

00:02:32.993 --> 00:02:35.562
(suspenseful music)

00:02:35.596 --> 00:02:39.566
The estimated point
of impact is Tokyo.

00:02:39.600 --> 00:02:41.969
With the ISS drawing near,

00:02:42.002 --> 00:02:45.138
the Digi-destined are the
only ones who can stop it.

00:02:46.607 --> 00:02:49.443
(horns blaring)

00:02:49.476 --> 00:02:52.913
(crowd chattering)

00:02:52.946 --> 00:02:54.915
And we still don't know
where it's landing?

00:02:56.183 --> 00:02:59.319
Not yet, we're still
trying to figure it out.

00:02:59.353 --> 00:03:00.921
Moscow reporting.

00:03:00.954 --> 00:03:03.490
Why haven't you commanded a
shift to the ISS trajectory?

00:03:03.524 --> 00:03:05.259
[Houston Technician]
It's too late.

00:03:05.292 --> 00:03:07.261
We can't do anything
at this point.

00:03:07.294 --> 00:03:08.495
This is Tsukuba.

00:03:08.529 --> 00:03:10.664
The thermal control
system isn't working.

00:03:10.697 --> 00:03:12.933
At this rate, there's
a very real possibility

00:03:12.966 --> 00:03:14.334
the station may explode.

00:03:14.368 --> 00:03:16.169
We're all well aware of that.

00:03:16.203 --> 00:03:18.939
What we don't know is where
in Tokyo it will land.

00:03:18.972 --> 00:03:21.842
All our control systems
have failed to work.

00:03:21.875 --> 00:03:24.378
All we can do at
this point is pray.

00:03:25.379 --> 00:03:28.282
(suspenseful music)

00:03:28.315 --> 00:03:30.484
Huh?

00:03:30.517 --> 00:03:32.686
Over here!

00:03:32.719 --> 00:03:35.656
(computer beeping)

00:03:45.566 --> 00:03:46.700
You found these?

00:03:46.733 --> 00:03:47.734
What are they?

00:03:49.736 --> 00:03:52.339
[Agumon] Whoa, crazy!

00:03:52.372 --> 00:03:55.208
[T.K.] Are they Digimon fossils?

00:03:56.410 --> 00:03:59.046
I bet those fossils are
from ancient Digimon.

00:03:59.079 --> 00:04:00.814
And because they
were so massive,

00:04:00.847 --> 00:04:03.717
their fossils are
still intact even now.

00:04:03.750 --> 00:04:05.218
I wonder what Digimon they were.

00:04:05.252 --> 00:04:07.387
They aren't gonna
start moving, right?

00:04:07.421 --> 00:04:08.855
Fossils aren't alive.

00:04:10.023 --> 00:04:11.892
Maybe it's the way
they're facing?

00:04:11.925 --> 00:04:14.828
But it looks like they're
in the middle of a battle.

00:04:14.861 --> 00:04:17.230
[Sora] Do you think these
fossils have something to do

00:04:17.264 --> 00:04:19.566
with the ancient battle
against Millenniummon?

00:04:20.400 --> 00:04:21.868
No.

00:04:21.902 --> 00:04:24.171
Battles between Digimon
here in the Digital World

00:04:24.204 --> 00:04:27.341
are not only between
light and dark.

00:04:27.374 --> 00:04:29.710
Digimon are constantly
fighting one another

00:04:29.743 --> 00:04:32.179
for survival, power,

00:04:32.212 --> 00:04:34.281
and, at times, even pride.

00:04:36.049 --> 00:04:37.017
But, look!

00:04:37.050 --> 00:04:38.251
In the sky over there.

00:04:38.285 --> 00:04:40.621
Do you see that giant
glowing pillar of light?

00:04:43.757 --> 00:04:45.225
Mm.

00:04:45.258 --> 00:04:47.361
I imagine that the
tremendous energy

00:04:47.394 --> 00:04:50.030
produced by the clash
of those two Digimon

00:04:50.063 --> 00:04:52.733
pierced the heavens and
even distorted space.

00:04:52.766 --> 00:04:55.068
And even now, after
all these years,

00:04:55.102 --> 00:04:56.903
its effects are still lingering.

00:04:58.472 --> 00:04:59.906
[Tentomon] Izzy
sure has been doing

00:04:59.940 --> 00:05:03.577
an awful lot of research
ever since he got here.

00:05:03.610 --> 00:05:04.611
So then, what do you think

00:05:04.645 --> 00:05:06.780
is at the top of
that pillar of light?

00:05:06.813 --> 00:05:08.115
Ooh, tell 'em, Izzy!

00:05:08.148 --> 00:05:10.250
That's the most
important part, isn't it?

00:05:10.283 --> 00:05:11.952
(monitor beeping)

00:05:11.985 --> 00:05:15.922
The top of that pillar of light
is basically a singularity

00:05:15.956 --> 00:05:18.125
leading outside of
the Digital World,

00:05:18.158 --> 00:05:21.561
to a place where the Network
is exposed and vulnerable.

00:05:21.595 --> 00:05:22.963
If I'm correct,

00:05:22.996 --> 00:05:25.966
we should be able to interact
with our world from there.

00:05:25.999 --> 00:05:27.467
What does that mean?

00:05:27.501 --> 00:05:30.804
It means we can do all sorts
of things to the human world

00:05:30.837 --> 00:05:33.306
while still being in
the Digital World.

00:05:33.340 --> 00:05:35.742
And one of those things is-

00:05:35.776 --> 00:05:37.978
[Izzy] We can change
the ISS's trajectory

00:05:38.011 --> 00:05:39.946
from within the Network

00:05:39.980 --> 00:05:43.950
the same way we were able to
prevent Tokyo's missile crash.

00:05:43.984 --> 00:05:46.753
(air whooshing)

00:05:46.787 --> 00:05:47.988
(radar beeping)

00:05:48.021 --> 00:05:50.457
Okay, I think I
get the rough idea.

00:05:50.490 --> 00:05:53.627
But how are we actually
supposed to stop that thing?

00:05:53.660 --> 00:05:55.128
If I'm being honest here,

00:05:55.162 --> 00:05:58.031
I don't even remember what I
did during the missile crisis.

00:05:59.299 --> 00:06:02.169
The data distorted
by Digimon's power

00:06:02.202 --> 00:06:04.438
will be fixed by
Digimon's power.

00:06:04.471 --> 00:06:07.274
(suspenseful music)

00:06:07.307 --> 00:06:09.676
We're going to snipe
the ISS control point

00:06:09.710 --> 00:06:12.179
inside the Network
at a precise angle.

00:06:13.213 --> 00:06:16.116
We may even be able to shift
its path toward the ocean

00:06:16.149 --> 00:06:17.984
without destroying the station.

00:06:18.018 --> 00:06:19.986
(monitor beeping)

00:06:20.020 --> 00:06:20.987
Terrific!

00:06:21.021 --> 00:06:22.189
Now, what does "snipe" mean?

00:06:22.222 --> 00:06:24.691
It means to target
and shoot something.

00:06:24.725 --> 00:06:26.626
Except we're not
going to destroy it,

00:06:26.660 --> 00:06:28.195
we're going to divert it, right?

00:06:28.228 --> 00:06:29.863
Right, and if we succeed,

00:06:29.896 --> 00:06:32.666
then the city should also
be safe from any debris.

00:06:32.699 --> 00:06:36.036
[T.K.] Which means no one
in Tokyo will be in danger.

00:06:36.069 --> 00:06:37.671
That's incredible, Izzy!

00:06:37.704 --> 00:06:39.639
I knew you'd come up with a plan

00:06:39.673 --> 00:06:42.142
But we only have one
chance to do this.

00:06:42.175 --> 00:06:43.543
There's no room for mistakes.

00:06:43.577 --> 00:06:45.145
It has to be perfect.

00:06:45.178 --> 00:06:47.180
Not to mention there are
several uncertainties

00:06:47.214 --> 00:06:49.015
I haven't worked out yet.

00:06:49.049 --> 00:06:50.317
And there's no guarantee

00:06:50.350 --> 00:06:51.885
this will actually
work in practice.

00:06:51.918 --> 00:06:55.388
So this whole operation
is a huge gamble then?

00:06:55.422 --> 00:06:56.823
(Sora gasping)

00:06:56.857 --> 00:06:59.226
But if somehow we can
get a little closer,

00:06:59.259 --> 00:07:00.527
it'd be more accurate.

00:07:01.428 --> 00:07:02.996
We only have 20 minutes left

00:07:03.029 --> 00:07:05.398
until the ISS passes
through the snipe point.

00:07:06.533 --> 00:07:08.902
That's not very long.

00:07:08.935 --> 00:07:10.403
20 minutes, huh?

00:07:11.404 --> 00:07:13.340
That's more than enough for us.

00:07:16.543 --> 00:07:17.511
Huh?

00:07:17.544 --> 00:07:18.645
(Agumon grunting)

00:07:18.678 --> 00:07:19.679
Let's do it!

00:07:21.515 --> 00:07:23.350
Agumon digivolve to...

